Here is a basic example of how you could define something for the script:

```csharp
public class brainPart2 : MonoBehaviour
{
    private Vector3 originalPos;
    public static TextMesh text;

    private bool isThisRed = false;
    private bool inTransition = false;

    void Start()
    {
        // Store the original position of the object
        originalPos = transform.position;

        // Assume that there is a TextMesh on the same gameObject with a reference to it
        text = GetComponent<TextMesh>();
    }

    void Update()
    {
        // Check for user input and move the object or whatever you need
        if (Input.GetKeyDown(KeyCode.Space))
        {
            StartCoroutine(MoveObject());
        }
    }

    IEnumerator MoveObject()
    {
        if (!inTransition)
        {
            inTransition = true;

            // This will wait 1 second before continuing
            yield return new WaitForSeconds(1f);

            // Move to a new position
            transform.position = new Vector3(0, 0, 0);

            // Change the color of the object if it's not already red
            if (!isThisRed)
            {
                isThisRed = true;
                GetComponent<Renderer>().material.color = Color.red;
            }

            // Change the text of the TextMesh component
            text.text = "Hello, world!";

            // Reset inTransition
            inTransition = false;
        }
    }
}
```

This script will find a `TextMesh` component on the same gameObject and set its text to "Hello, world!" when you press the space key. It will also move the gameObject on its y-axis to (0, 0, 0) and change its color to red if it's not already. It won't do anything if it's already in the middle of a transition. 

Remember, the DG.Tweening library (which is used in the example code) is only used for its `WaitForSeconds` method which is also available in Unity's built-in functions. To use DOTween, you need to import it in your Unity project from the Unity Asset Store or Github page.
